<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,978,1365]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
The most obvious differences are in the morphology of the mandibular palp, G1 and G2 and P6 and P7, as detailed for the specimen described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E." box="[595,811,1051,1078]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" pagination="107 - 151" refId="ref4540" refString="Vinogradov, M. E. (1964) Hyperiidea Physosomata from the northern part of the Indian Ocean. Trudy Instituta Okeanologii Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 65, 107 - 151. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1964">Vinogradov (1964)</bibRefCitation>
, except that the dactylus of G1 and G2 are partially retractile and the basis of P6 and P7 seems to be without a small proximal bulge (Gasca pers. comm.). In addition; for P5 the distal margin of the propodus is more acute at the insertion of the dactylus; P6 and P7 are relatively much longer than P5 (sub-equal or only slightly longer for current specimens); for P7 the merus and carpus are sub-equal in length and slightly shorter than the propodus (the merus is clearly longer than the carpus and slightly longer than the propodus in the current specimens); for U2 the endopod is relatively shorter (about 0.6 x vs. 0.9 x peduncle length); the serrations on the peduncle and rami of the uropods are more prominent and the peduncle and endopod of U3 is not as broad. The other differences noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gasca, R. &amp; Haddock, S. H. D." box="[748,1035,1303,1330]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" pagination="138 - 144" refId="ref4434" refString="Gasca, R. &amp; Haddock, S. H. D. (2016) The rare deep-living amphipod Megalanceoloides remipes (Barnard, 1932): complementary description and symbiosis. Zootaxa, 4178 (1), 138 - 144. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4178.1.7" type="journal article" year="2016">Gasca &amp; Haddock (2016)</bibRefCitation>
are considered minor and alone not significant at the species level.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
